1. A direction vector \(\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \end{pmatrix}\) corresponds to a slope of \(\frac{b}{a}\).
2. We need \(\frac{b}{a} = -\frac{7}{4}\), or equivalently:
   \[ a \cdot \frac{b}{a} = -\frac{7}{4} \Longleftrightarrow b \cdot 4 = -7 \cdot a \Longleftrightarrow b = -\frac{7}{4} \cdot a \]

Let's check which of the vectors satisfy this condition. 

\(\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix}\)
\begin{align*}
\frac{7}{4} &\neq -\frac{7}{4} \Longleftrightarrow \text{this is not a direction vector.}
\end{align*}

\(\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}\)
\begin{align*}
\frac{4}{7} &\neq -\frac{7}{4} \Longleftrightarrow \text{this is not a direction vector.}
\end{align*}

\(\begin{pmatrix} -4/7 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}\)
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{-\frac{4}{7}} &= -\frac{7}{4} \Longleftrightarrow \text{this is a direction vector.}
\end{align*}

\(\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 7/4 \end{pmatrix}\)
\begin{align*}
\frac{\frac{7}{4}}{1} &= \frac{7}{4} \neq -\frac{7}{4} \Longleftrightarrow \text{this is not a direction vector.}
\end{align*}

\(\begin{pmatrix} 14 \\ -8 \end{pmatrix}\)
\begin{align*}
\frac{-8}{14} &= -\frac{4}{7} \neq -\frac{7}{4} \Longleftrightarrow \text{this is not a direction vector.}
\end{align*}

\(\begin{pmatrix} -12 \\ 21 \end{pmatrix}\)
\begin{align*}
\frac{21}{-12} &= -\frac{7}{4} \Longleftrightarrow \text{this is a direction vector.}
\end{align*}

\(\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ -7/2 \end{pmatrix}\)
\begin{align*}
\frac{-\frac{7}{2}}{-2} &= \frac{7}{4} \neq -\frac{7}{4} \Longleftrightarrow \text{this is not a direction vector.}
\end{align*}

\(\begin{pmatrix} -1/3 \\ 7/12 \end{pmatrix}\)
\begin{align*}
\frac{\frac{7}{12}}{-\frac{1}{3}} &= -\frac{7}{4} \Longleftrightarrow \text{this is a direction vector.}
\end{align*}

